 Lenzi offers a microhistory of an ethnic radical group during the heyday of labor radicalism in the United States. He also places that history in the context of the larger radical movement, the Italian American community, and greater American society, as it moved from the Gilded Age to the New Deal and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAnarchistszConnecticutzNew London. 0aItalian AmericanszConnecticutzNew LondonxHistory. 4aAmerican Studies : Italian American Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : Ethnic History. 4aPublic Policy : Immigration. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / New England (CT, MA, ME, NH, RI, VT).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847272040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472720423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472720/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles